    "description": "<p>Ibn Sina (Avicenna, d. 427/1038) is both the most original and most influential philosopher in Islam. His philosophical system had a huge impact on a great number of Islamic discourses up until the twentieth century. This reading seminar introduces students to one particular theme of Ibn Sina\u2019s philosophy and to the methods of researching it. We focus on Ibn Sina\u2019s proof for God\u2019s existence and its implication for his conception of the divine attributes. We also devote time to the criticism this concept attracted from other Islamic thinkers, particularly from Ash\u2018arite and Mu\u2018tazilite theologians such as al-Ghazali (d. 505/1111), Fakhr al-Din al-Razi (d. 606/1210), and Ibn al-Malahimi (d. 536/1141). Students gain a basic understanding of the most important competing concepts of the divine attributes in Islam (Mu\u2018tazilite, Ash\u2018arite, and Avicennan). Reading of primary sources in Arabic is accompanied by discussion of secondary literature in English and other Western languages.</p>\n<p class=\"prerequisites\">Prerequisites: reading command of Arabic and permission of the instructor.</p>",
